body:
## Steps to Reproduce

Hit the debug button and it always shows the `starting devtools` popup (each time it gets restarted), which may seem like the duplication of #5234, but I think it's the desired behavior?

After started, the simulator shows nothing, and the console output (no `Debug service listening` nor `Syncing files to device...`:

```
Launching lib/main.dart on iPhone 12 Pro Max in debug mode...
Running Xcode build...
Xcode build done.    
```

Here comes the most confusing part, after some seconds or minutes, it suddenly prints an `Activating Dart DevTools...` message in the debug console, then it will get stuck.

After some digging, I find that the plugin has executed the command `pub.dart.snapshot global activate devtools` more than once, then I killed the extra process and it finally works. 

so my question is, is it normal to have the `starting devtools` popup each time I restart it? and why does it try to activate the Devtool even when I have activated it globally?

Thanks!

comment_data.body: @helin24 Are we checking to see if DevTools is activated before we try to activate it? See [this method](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/master/packages/flutter_tools/lib/src/devtools_launcher.dart#L156) in flutter_tools for an example of only attempting to activate DevTools if it is not active or if it has been more than N hours since the last time we tried (we may already be doing this in IntelliJ - I can't remember).

@kenzieschmoll ok...now I think I have figured it out.

the Devtools was not installed in the first place, and it would take some time to download it, but it didn't use the proxy, so it got stuck.

since I can't wait too long, I stopped the debug process. **But it didn't kill the background job that is fetching the Devtools**, which left a zombie process unless I kill it manually.

in this case, each time I try to start the debug, the background process would always get in the way

I find it because after killing all the processes related to the `pub xxx` and run the debug, everything works smoothly.
@helin24 maybe we should be killing the devtools process if a user clicks Stop before the process to serve devtools has completed

It sounds like there are a few things going on here:
1. Is this on the latest version of the Flutter plugin? In v54 we skip waiting for DevTools to start on pressing debug after the first time a project is run. This doesn't fix whether DevTools gets started/canceled during the first attempt though.
2. It sounds like you also need a proxy to download DevTools properly - is this something you've set up, e.g. using these [instructions](https://flutter.dev/community/china), if you're working in China? And are able to use DevTools, e.g. if you start an app from the command line or after you've started successfully running an app in IntelliJ?
3. Can you describe how you stopped the debug process early? IntelliJ should be locked while the "Starting DevTools.." message is up.

@helin24 thank you for your reply! as for the question:

1. sure, it's the latest version, flutter v54, dart v201.9335
2. hmm, I managed to download it in the separate terminal app, and I started it from the Android Studio, they should work the same.
3. I stopped the debug process after it shows the "Starting DevTools..", but before the plugin starts the Devtools. it's weird that it doesn't show the message (Activating Devtools...) immediately but after some random time.

@helin24 well...I think there is a misunderstanding, maybe the Devtools should be started before the "Starting DevTools..." popup disappears, BUT...mine would disappear even if the Devtools not get installed or started, that's the point.

then I simply clicked the red square button to stop the debug...

so it prints the "Activating DevTools" message after the "Starting DevTools..." disappears, with random delay.

>Not sure why there would be multiple pub activations in this case.

Hmmm, I guess it's because it doesn't kill the downloading process, each time I stopped the debug, it will stack up.

Ah I see, this makes more sense. There's a timeout on "Starting DevTools.." so that we don't permanently block starting the app if DevTools startup is very slow or fails. If startup is slow, we let it continue in the background since we still want to have an instance of DevTools for your project. i think what could be happening is DevTools fails to start for your project, and then we try to start DevTools from the app again since we were unable to send a DevTools URL to the app. 

So does this happen consistently each time you open a project? i.e. The "Starting DevTools" popup appears the first time you run/debug your app, times out, and then you get the many pub processes? Or does this happen intermittently and get fixed once you kill the pub processes?

This DevTools opening process has been changed pretty significantly since this issue was last discussed. I'm going to close this issue since problems with this using the latest plugin with stable Flutter will require a different discussion.
